{{see|liebe}}

==German==
<!-- ===Alternative spellings=== -->
===Etymology===

From Middle High German ''[[liebe]]'' (''the quality of love'', ''pleasure'', ''joy'', ''favour'', ''love''), from the Old High German ''[[liob]]'' \ ''[[lioba]]'' (''fortune'', ''health'', ''pleasantness'', ''joy''), from Germanic ''*leuba-'' \ ''*leubam'' (''love''), from Proto-Indo-European ''*leub<sup>h</sup>-'', a verb meaning ''to enjoy'', ''to long for''.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈliːbə/}}, ''plural'': {{IPA|ˈliːbən}}
*:Hyphenation: Lie·be, ''plural'': Lie·ben
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:German:iːbə|iːbə]], ''plural'': [[Rhymes:German:iːbən|iːbən]]
*Homophones : (''in some dialects of German'') [[leben|lebe]]
*{{audio|De-Liebe.ogg|Audio : Liebe}}

===Noun===
'''Liebe''' {{f}}, ''plural'': die [[Lieben]], ''genitive singular'': der [[Liebe]]

# (''no plural'') [[love]] (''tender feeling of affection'')
#* '''1787''' [[CE]]: Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, ''Egmont''
#*: ''Und konnte ich fürchten, daß diese unglückliche '''Liebe''' das kluge Klärchen so bald hinreißen würde?  Ich muß es nun tragen, daß meine Tochter--''
#*:: ''And could I imagine, that is unhappy '''love''' would so soon carry away the prudent little Klara?  I must endure it mnow, that my daughter--''
# (''no plural'') [[lust]] (''sexually or erotically motivated inclination'')
## (''no plural'') [[sexual intercourse]] (bodily union as a result of [[lust]])
# {{colloquial}}: ''short for'' [[love]] [[affair]]
# [[love]] (''term of endearment'')
# (''plural'') [[love|loves]], [[loved one|loved ones]] (''members of one's family or close friends'')
#* '''1784''' [[CE]]: Johann Christoph Friedrich von Schiller, ''Kabale und Liebe''
#*: ''Ihr steht bestürzt, guten Leute, erwartet angstvoll, wie sich das Räthsel entwickeln wird?--Kommt näher, meine '''Lieben'''!--Ihr dientet mir redlich und warm [...]''
#*:: ''You stand dismayed, good people, worry fearfully how the riddle will develop?--Come closer, my '''loves'''!--You served me fairly and warmly [...]''
